=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-==-=-=-
iv. The regression equation.

The Regression equation :

Autism Prevalence = 0.2231322 * (Year - 1992)^2 + 3.9848276

=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-==-=-=-
### v. Interpretation of the slope and intercept in the model (regression equation.)
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-==-=-=-

The slope represents the rate of change [per (year-reference year of 1992)^2 ] in autism per 10,000 10-year-old US children for the five-year period of the study. In other words, for each succeeding year after 1992 (refernce year) the autism prevalence increases as a function of (year-1992)^2.

The intercept in this case is simply the model (expected) level of Autism Prevalence in the Reference Year of 1992, (Year 0) for this model. In this case, the models value = 3.9848276

### xii. Provide a measure of the amount of variation in the response that is accounted for by the explanatory variable. Interpret this measure clearly indicating the units of the response and the explanatory variables.
=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-==-=-=-

r2 <- summary.lm(fit_all, r.squared=TRUE)$r.squared
r2_format <- sprintf("%8.2f %%", r2*100)
non_r2_format <- sprintf("%8.2f %%", (1.0 - r2)*100)

R-squared value for model = 0.9962461

Therefore, 99.62 % of the variation observed in the dependent variable (Autism Prevalence) is explained by the increasing yearly count (with 1992 as the reference year) independent variable, leaving only 0.38 % variation that is available to be explained by any remaining contributory factors.
